# `&&`, `||`, `=>` and `? :` evaluate only what they have to.
#
# They used to lower to `select`, which is a value and not a branch: both
# operands were materialised into the same block and the operator chose
# between them afterwards. While every expression is total -- a load at a
# fixed offset, arithmetic, a comparison -- that is not a shortcut but the
# better lowering, branchless and schedulable. REF's expressions were total,
# so nothing was wrong with it.
#
# Two things had stopped being total. Every requirement below aborted the
# process before short-circuiting, and none of them is exotic: each is the
# obvious way to write "check this only where it makes sense".

data x    : integer;
data y    : integer;
data rows : integer[][];

# ── Division ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# x is 0 at the second state. The division ran regardless of the guard and
# raised SIGFPE -- which has been true since long before arrays carried their
# own length, and has nothing to do with them.
G(x != 0 => y / x > 1);
G(x != 0 ? y / x > 1 : true);
G(x == 0 || y / x > 1);

# ── An index past the end ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# rows has two rows at the first state, one at the second, none at the third.
# `rows[1]` where there is no second row reads a descriptor that was never
# written, and the next step dereferences it. A padded array made this a wrong
# byte; a ragged one makes it a wild pointer.
G(rows.count > 1 => rows[1][0] > 0);
G(rows.count > 1 ? rows[1][0] > 0 : true);
G(rows.count == 0 || rows[0][0] > 0);

# ── The order is the specification's, not the compiler's ─────────────────────
# A guard guards what follows it, and only that. Written the other way round
#
#     G((y / x > 1) && x != 0);
#
# still aborts, and should: the reading of `&&` that makes everything above
# work is the same reading that leaves this one the author's mistake. It is not
# in this file because it would take the process with it.
#
# The guard also composes, which is what makes it usable: both the antecedent
# and the consequent below are reached only where the count allows.
G(rows.count > 1 && rows[1][0] > 0 => rows[1][0] > 0);
G(x != 0 && y != 0 => y / x > 1);

# ── Both operands still agree with the answer ────────────────────────────────
# Short-circuiting must not change a verdict, only what is reached. These are
# the ordinary cases, where both sides are safe either way.
G((x > 1 && y > 1) == (y > 1 && x > 1));
G((x > 1 || y > 1) == (y > 1 || x > 1));
G((x > 100 && y > 1) == false);
G((x >= 0 || y > 100) == true);
G((x > 1 ? y : 0 - y) == (x > 1 ? y : 0 - y));
